{{Infobox mountain | name = San Vicente | other_name = ''Chichontepec'' | photo = San vicente els.jpg | photo_caption = San Vicente in 1994 | elevation_m = 2182 | elevation_ref = <ref name=gvp>{{cite gvp|vnum=1403-07=|name=San Vicente|accessdate=2010-04-16}}</ref> | prominence = | listing = [[Breast-shaped hill]]s | location = [[El Salvador]] | range = | map = El Salvador | map_caption = Location in El Salvador | label_position = bottom | coordinates = {{coord|13.595|N|88.837|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = <ref name=gvp/> | topo = | type = [[Stratovolcano]] | age = | last_eruption = Unknown<ref name=gvp/> | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
'''San Vicente''' (also known as '''Chichontepec''' or '''Las Chiches''') is a [[stratovolcano]] in central [[El Salvador]]. It is located next to the town of San Vicente (hence the name) and is the second highest volcano in El Salvador. In the indigenous language [[Nahuat]], Chichontepec means ''the mountain of the two breasts'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geo.mtu.edu/volcanoes/central_america/el_salvador/san_vicente/|title=San Vicente|publisher=[[Michigan Technological University]]|accessdate=2012-05-13}}</ref> because its [[double summit]] resembles a woman's bosom. The volcano has two [[Volcanic crater|crater]]s, one located in each summit, although not exactly at the top. Dense vegetation covers both summits. Numerous [[hot spring]]s and [[fumarole]]s are found on the northern and western flanks of the volcano. To the northeast, at 820 metres in a ravine of 180 metres longitude, there are fumaroles—fountains of clear and muddy water or small volcanoes of mud.
The last significant eruption occurred more than 1,700 years ago. The volcano may have had a very long history of repeated, and sometimes violent, eruptions, and at least once a large section of the volcano collapsed in a massive landslide.<ref name=usgs>{{cite web|url=http://vulcan.wr.usgs.gov/Volcanoes/ElSalvador/Publications/OFR01-367/past_events_san_vicente.html|title=Volcano-Hazard Zonation for San Vicente Volcano, El Salvador|authors=J.J. Major, S.P. Schilling, C.R. Pullinger, C.D. Escobar, and M.M. Howell|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey|USGS]]|accessdate=2009-11-13}}</ref>
On August 9, 1995, [[Aviateca Flight 901]] crashed at the volcano, killing all 65 people on board.<ref>http://www.elsalvador.com/Especiales/2010/TragediaSanVicente/nota3.asp</ref>
